main event: Radar observation of unidentified objects near Wiesbaden, Germany on July 7, 1950
interesting points: The GCA radar detected the objects at an altitude of approximately 11,000 feet and they were observed for around 15-20 minutes.
The objects appeared to separate into 4 or 5 blurred individual targets, spaced 900 to 1000 yards apart, and were moving at an extremely high speed of approximately 2,000 to 3,000 miles per hour.

The high speed of the objects suggested the possibility of them being jet aircraft, but the Wiesbaden control tower operator stated that no jet aircraft were known to be flying in the area at that time.
An airman of the 1947th AACS Squadron reported hearing sounds similar to those made by low-flying jet aircraft at about 2300Z on the same day, without advance knowledge of the radar observation.
The report states that the targets were then lost from sight, approximately 21:07 as the operation's concentration shift.
witnesses: USAF personnel, including a GCA crew and a security officer
